                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/3576.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Consul at Chihuahua</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Chihuahua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-04-11T20:00:00-07:04">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 11, 1912—8 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> (Received, via El Paso, Tex., April 13, 1912—2.18 a.m.)</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Orozco, rebel military commander, has just sent me a most remarkable letter
                    saying that in view of nonrecognition belligerency on the part of the United
                    States the rebel government would refuse to recognize consular representatives
                    of the United States, and that henceforth I should not address the military
                    commander on behalf of my Government. This letter was received an hour after
                    delivery my note respecting detention American engineer at Jimenez and purports
                    to be in answer to my protest against the seizure of mail.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Letcher.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
